ce:section.ce:para:
EIS is effective technique in explaining the process of electrode modification. In general, the interfacial properties of biosensors have a significant impact on the amount of immobilized aptamer. In this work, the new nanocomposites, CDs-BP, were used as sensing platform to load the amount of OTA aptamers. The electrode self-assembly process is well recorded by the electrochemical impedance spectroscopy in 0.1 M PBS solution containing 1 mM redox probe [Fe(CN)6]3-/4-. As shown in Fig. 3
                        , the interface is modeled using the Randle model modified with Warburg impedance (Zw
                        ) (see inset model). This circuit includes the interface capacitance (C), the ohmic resistance of the electrolyte solution (Rs
                        ), the Warburg impedance (Zw
                        ) manifested as straight line, and the charge-transfer resistance (Rct
                        ) manifested as the semicircle. The impedance spectra (Nyquist plots) show a semicircle and straight line in each self-assembly steps. The bare GCE showed a small semicircle diameter about 300.3 ohm (curve a), indicating that the redox probe [Fe(CN)6]3-/4- reached to the treated bare GCE surface easily and GCE has a good electrical conductivity. The CDs-BP/GCE (curve b) exhibits weak electrical conductivity, illustrating that CDs-BP prevents the electron transfer from [Fe(CN)6]3-/4- to the electrode surface. Therefore, the semicircle diameter of the modified electrode (699.1 ohm) is bigger than that of the bare electrode. The diameter of the semicircle (1652.4 ohm, curve c) changed again after fixing the aptamer on the CDs-BP nanocomposites. Subsequently, when the electrode was incubated in the 0.1 pg/mL OTA solution, the OTA the aptamer specifically recognized OTA and leaded to release aptamer from the surface of the CDs-BP nanocomposites, which caused the semicircle diameter of OTA/Aptamer/CDs-BP/GCE sensor to decrease to 1144.3 ohm (curve d). As we all known, the larger the diameter of the semicircle, the greater the impedance value, and the smaller the corresponding current [42].
